80-86515-61-3 |language = Czech|pages= |url= }}\n*{{cite book|title= The Czechs and the Lands of the Bohemian Crown|last= Agnew|first= Hugh LeCaine|authorlink= |year= 2004|publisher= Hoover Institution Press|location= Stanford|isbn= 0-8179-4492-3|language= |pages= |url= https://archive.org/details/czechslandsofboh00agne|url-access= registration}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.worldstatesmen.org/Czech_Republic.html#Bohemia Kingdom of Bohemia at Worldstatesmen]\n\n{{Electors of the Holy Roman Empire after 1356}}\n{{Provinces of the Austrian Empire}}\n{{Subdivisions of Austria-Hungary}}\n\n{{coord missing|Czech Republic}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kingdom Of Bohemia}}\n[[Category:Kingdom of Bohemia| ]]\n[[Category:History of Bohemia]]\n[[Category:Medieval Kingdom of Bohemia]]\n[[Category:Kingdoms and countries of Austria-Hungary|Bohemia]]\n[[Category:Cisleithania]]\n[[Category:Monarchy of the Holy Roman Empire|Bohemia]]\n[[Category:Former kingdoms|Bohemia]]\n[[Category:Former Slavic countries]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1198]]\n[[Category:States and territories disestablished in 1918]]\n[[Category:1198 establishments in Europe]]\n[[Category:1190s establishments in the Holy Roman Empire]]\n[[Category:1918 disestablishments in Austria-Hungary]]\n[[Category:2nd millennium in Bohemia]]\n[[Category:Lands of the Bohemian Crown]]\n", "name_user": "2a00:1028:838c:cdc6:3cf5:fd03:f706:fb4e", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Undid revision 949403176 byM-Mustapha(talk) - I believe the reasoning explained on M-Mustapha's talk page is sufficient, and the previous explanation stands)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kingdom_of_Bohemia"}
{"title_page": "Integer complexity", "text_new": "In [[number theory]], the '''integer complexity''' of an [[integer]] is the smallest number of [[1 (number)|ones]] that can be used to represent it using ones and any number of [[addition]]s, [[multiplication]]s, and parentheses. It is always within a constant factor of the [[logarithm]] of the given integer.\n\nAlso, there exist one more definition of complexity. Complexity of an integer n   is the    minimum number of steps required to get n, where at each step one can either calculate a sum or a product of any two previously obtained numbers. The first number in the set to be one. Upper bound to complexity by new definition is 3*ln(n)\\ln(ln(n)).\n\n==Example==\nFor instance, the number 11 may be represented using eight ones:\n:11 = (1 + 1 + 1) &times; (1 + 1 + 1) + 1 + 1.\nHowever, it has no representation using seven or fewer ones. Therefore, its complexity is eight.\n\nThe complexities of the numbers 1, 2, 3, ... are\n:1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 5, 6, 6, 6, 7, 8, 7, 8, 8, 8, 8, 9, 8, ... {{OEIS| A005245}}\n\nThe smallest numbers with complexity 1, 2, 3, ... are\n:1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 7, 10, 11, 17, 22, 23, 41, 47, ... {{OEIS|A005520}}\n\nBy new approach, the number 11 be represented using for steps:\n:[1] 1+1 = 2\n:[2] 1+2 = 3\n:[3] 3*3 = 9\n:[4] 2+9 = 11\nFor proof that one can not get 11 less then 4 steps we check all numbers with complexity less then 4:\n:Complexity 0:   1\n:Complexity 1:   2\n:Complexity 2:   3, 4\n:Complexity 3:   5, 6, 8, 9, 16\n\nThe upper bound for complexity you can see in this link: http://nbashaev.pythonanywhere.com/integer_complexity/\n\nThe smallest numbers with complexity 1, 2, 3, ... are\n: 2, 3, 5, 7, 13, 23, 59, 211, 619.\nAlso, Mordosevich's hypothesis try to describes all of smallest numbers.\n\n==Upper and lower bounds==\nThe question of expressing integers in this way was originally considered by {{harvtxt|Mahler|Popken|1953}}. They asked for the largest number with a given complexity {{mvar|k}};<ref>{{citation\n | last1 = Mahler | first1 = K. | author1-link = Kurt Mahler\n | last2 = Popken | first2 = J.\n | journal = Nieuw Archief voor Wiskunde\n | mr = 0053986\n | pages = 1\u201315\n | title = On a maximum problem in arithmetic\n | volume = 1\n | year = 1953}}.</ref> later, Selfridge showed that this number is\n:<math>2^x3^{(k-2x)/3} \\text{ where } x = -k\\bmod 3.</math>\nFor example, when {{math|1=''k'' = 10}}, {{math|1=''x'' = 2}} and the largest integer that can be expressed using ten ones is {{math|1=2{{sup|2}}{{hsp}}3{{sup|2}} = 36}}. Its expression is\n:(1 + 1) &times; (1 + 1) &times; (1 + 1 + 1) &times; (1 + 1 + 1).\nThus, the complexity of an integer {{mvar|n}} is at least {{math|3{{hsp}}log{{sub|3}}{{hsp}}''n''}}.  The complexity of {{mvar|n}} is at most {{math|3{{hsp}}log{{sub|2}}{{hsp}}''n''}} (approximately {{math|4.755{{hsp}}log{{sub|3}}{{hsp}}''n''}}): an expression of this length for {{mvar|n}} can be found by applying [[Horner's method]] to the [[binary representation]] of {{mvar|n}}.<ref name=\"guy\">{{citation\n | last = Guy | first = Richard K. | authorlink = Richard K. Guy\n | department = Unsolved Problems\n | doi = 10.2307/2323338\n | issue = 3\n | journal = [[American Mathematical Monthly]]\n | mr = 1540817\n | pages = 186\u2013190\n | title = Some suspiciously simple sequences\n | volume = 93\n | year = 1986}}.</ref> Almost all integers have a representation whose length is bounded by a logarithm with a smaller constant factor, {{math|3.529{{hsp}}log{{sub|3}}{{hsp}}''n''}}.<ref>{{citation|first=Christopher E.|last=Shriver|year=2015|title=Applications of Markov chain analysis to integer complexity|arxiv=1511.07842|bibcode=2015arXiv151107842S}}.</ref>\n\nBy new approach, now gived asymptotically optimal monotonous upper and lower bounds but we do not know something about not-monotonous bounds.\n\nThe largest number with complexity n $\\in$ $\\mathbb{N}$ is $2^{2^{n}}$ (the largest number with complexity 0 is 1). For proof you can use induction, also, Andrey Mordosevich proof this.\n\nAbout the lower bound, it is f = k*($\\frac{ln(n)}{ln(ln(n))}$, $\\frac{1}{2}$ < k < 3. Also, Andrey Mordosevich proof this.\n\nMordosevich's hyphotesis: All a is prime numbers, g>0. Where a = smallest number with complexity g.\n\n\n==Algorithms and counterexamples==\nThe complexities of all integers up to some threshold {{mvar|N}} can be calculated in total time {{math|''O''(''N''{{sup|1.222911236}})}}.<ref>{{citation|first1=K.|last=Cordwell|first2=A.|last2=Epstein|first3=A.|last3=Hemmady|first4=S.|last4=Miller|first5=E.|last5=Palsson|first6=A.|last6=Sharma|first7=S.|last7=Steinerberger|first8=Y.|last8=Vu|title=On algorithms to calculate integer complexity|year=2017|arxiv=1706.08424|bibcode=2017arXiv170608424C}}</ref>\n\nAlgorithms for computing the integer complexity have been used to disprove several conjectures about the complexity.\nIn particular, it is not necessarily the case that the optimal expression for a number {{mvar|n}} is obtained either by subtracting one from {{mvar|n}} or by expressing {{mvar|n}} as the product of two smaller factors. The smallest example of a number whose optimal expression is not of this form is 353942783. It is a [[prime number]], and therefore also disproves a conjecture of [[Richard K. Guy]] that the complexity of every prime number {{mvar|p}} is one plus the complexity of {{math|''p'' &minus; 1}}.<ref>{{citation|url=https://oeis.org/A005245/a005245.c.txt|title=Program to calculate A005245, A005520, A005421|first=Martin N.|last=Fuller|date=February 1, 2008|publisher=OEIS|accessdate=2015-12-13}}.</ref>\n\n==External links==\n*{{mathworld|title=Integer Complexity|id=IntegerComplexity}}\n*[https://www.mathworks.com/matlabcentral/fileexchange/49792-calculate-integer-complexity Matlab code for calculating integer complexity] and the paper explains the code <ref>{{citation|url=http://www.pspchv.com/content_PJNTA-vol-9-issues-1-2.html|title=MINIMUM OPERATIONS FOR COMPUTING INTEGER COMPLEXITY AND ITS APPLICATION\n|first=Zou|last=Qing|date=June 1, 2015|publisher=Pioneer Scientific|accessdate=2015-06-01}}.</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Integer sequences]]\n", "text_old": "In [[number theory]], the '''integer complexity''' of an [[integer]] is the smallest number of [[1 (number)|ones]] that can be used to represent it using ones and any number of [[addition]]s, [[multiplication]]s, and parentheses. It is always within a constant factor of the [[logarithm]] of the given integer.\n\nAlso, there exist one more definition of complexity. Complexity of an integer n   is the    minimum number of steps required to get n, where at each step one can either calculate a sum or a product of any two previously obtained numbers. The first number in the set to be one. Upper bound to complexity by new definition is 3*ln(n)\\ln(ln(n)).\n\n==Example==\nFor instance, the number 11 may be represented using eight ones:\n:11 = (1 + 1 + 1) &times; (1 + 1 + 1) + 1 + 1.\nHowever, it has no representation using seven or fewer ones. Therefore, its complexity is eight.\n\nThe complexities of the numbers 1, 2, 3, ... are\n:1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 5, 6, 6, 6, 7, 8, 7, 8, 8, 8, 8, 9, 8, ... {{OEIS| A005245}}\n\nThe smallest numbers with complexity 1, 2, 3, ... are\n:1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 7, 10, 11, 17, 22, 23, 41, 47, ... {{OEIS|A005520}}\n\nBy new approach, the number 11 be represented using for steps:\n:[1] 1+1 = 2\n:[2] 1+2 = 3\n:[3] 3*3 = 9\n:[4] 2+9 = 11\nFor proof that one can not get 11 less then 4 steps we check all numbers with complexity less then 4:\n:Complexity 0:   1\n:Complexity 1:   2\n:Complexity 2:   3, 4\n:Complexity 3:   5, 6, 8, 9, 16\n\nThe upper bound for complexity you can see in this link: http://nbashaev.pythonanywhere.com/integer_complexity/\n\nThe smallest numbers with complexity 1, 2, 3, ... are\n: 2, 3, 5, 7, 13, 23, 59, 211, 619.\nAlso, Mordosevich's hypothesis try to describes all of smallest numbers.\n\n==Upper and lower bounds==\nThe question of expressing integers in this way was originally considered by {{harvtxt|Mahler|Popken|1953}}. They asked for the largest number with a given complexity {{mvar|k}};<ref>{{citation\n | last1 = Mahler | first1 = K. | author1-link = Kurt Mahler\n | last2 = Popken | first2 = J.\n | journal = Nieuw Archief voor Wiskunde\n | mr = 0053986\n | pages = 1\u201315\n | title = On a maximum problem in arithmetic\n | volume = 1\n | year = 1953}}.</ref> later, Selfridge showed that this number is\n:<math>2^x3^{(k-2x)/3} \\text{ where } x = -k\\bmod 3.</math>\nFor example, when {{math|1=''k'' = 10}}, {{math|1=''x'' = 2}} and the largest integer that can be expressed using ten ones is {{math|1=2{{sup|2}}{{hsp}}3{{sup|2}} = 36}}. Its expression is\n:(1 + 1) &times; (1 + 1) &times; (1 + 1 + 1) &times; (1 + 1 + 1).\nThus, the complexity of an integer {{mvar|n}} is at least {{math|3{{hsp}}log{{sub|3}}{{hsp}}''n''}}.  The complexity of {{mvar|n}} is at most {{math|3{{hsp}}log{{sub|2}}{{hsp}}''n''}} (approximately {{math|4.755{{hsp}}log{{sub|3}}{{hsp}}''n''}}): an expression of this length for {{mvar|n}} can be found by applying [[Horner's method]] to the [[binary representation]] of {{mvar|n}}.<ref name=\"guy\">{{citation\n | last = Guy | first = Richard K. | authorlink = Richard K. Guy\n | department = Unsolved Problems\n | doi = 10.2307/2323338\n | issue = 3\n | journal = [[American Mathematical Monthly]]\n | mr = 1540817\n | pages = 186\u2013190\n | title = Some suspiciously simple sequences\n | volume = 93\n | year = 1986}}.</ref> Almost all integers have a representation whose length is bounded by a logarithm with a smaller constant factor, {{math|3.529{{hsp}}log{{sub|3}}{{hsp}}''n''}}.<ref>{{citation|first=Christopher E.|last=Shriver|year=2015|title=Applications of Markov chain analysis to integer complexity|arxiv=1511.07842|bibcode=2015arXiv151107842S}}.</ref>\n\nBy new approach, now gived asymptotically optimal monotonous upper and lower bounds but we do not know something about not-monotonous bounds.\n\nThe largest number with complexity n $\\in$ $\\mathbb{N}$ is $2^{2^{n}}$ (the largest number with complexity 0 is 1). For proof you can use induction, also, Andrey Mordosevich proof this.\n\nAbout the lower bound, it is f = k*($\\frac{ln(n)}{ln(ln(n))}$, $\\frac{1}{2}$ < k < 3. Also, Andrey Mordosevich proof this.\n\nMordosevich's hyphotesis: All a is prime numbers, g>0. Where a = smallest number with complexity g.\n\n\n==Algorithms and counterexamples==\nThe complexities of all integers up to some threshold {{mvar|N}} can be calculated in total time {{math|''O''(''N''{{sup|1.222911236}})}}.<ref>{{citation|first1=K.|last=Cordwell|first2=A.|last2=Epstein|first3=A.|last3=Hemmady|first4=S.|last4=Miller|first5=E.|last5=Palsson|first6=A.|last6=Sharma|first7=S.|last7=Steinerberger|first8=Y.|last8=Vu|title=On algorithms to calculate integer complexity|year=2017|arxiv=1706.08424|bibcode=2017arXiv170608424C}}</ref>\n\nAlgorithms for computing the integer complexity have been used to disprove several conjectures about the complexity.\nIn particular, it is not necessarily the case that the optimal expression for a number {{mvar|n}} is obtained either by subtracting one from {{mvar|n}} or by expressing {{mvar|n}} as the product of two smaller factors. The smallest example of a number whose optimal expression is not of this form is 353942783. It is a [[prime number]], and therefore also disproves a conjecture of [[Richard K. Guy]] that the complexity of every prime number {{mvar|p}} is one plus the complexity of {{math|''p'' &minus; 1}}.<ref>{{citation|url=https://oeis.org/A005245/a005245.c.txt|title=Program to calculate A005245, A005520, A005421|first=Martin N.|last=Fuller|date=February 1, 2008|publisher=OEIS|accessdate=2015-12-13}}.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{mathworld|title=Integer Complexity|id=IntegerComplexity}}\n*[https://www.mathworks.com/matlabcentral/fileexchange/49792-calculate-integer-complexity Matlab code for calculating integer complexity] \n\n[[Category:Integer sequences]]\n", "name_user": "J Steed Huang", "label": "safe", "comment": "add more reference", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer_complexity"}
{"title_page": "A Different Kind of Love Song", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = A Different Kind of Love Song\n| cover      = Adkols.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Cher]]\n| album      = [[Living Proof (Cher album)|Living Proof]]\n| A-side     = [[The Music's No Good Without You]]\n| released   = {{start date|2002|07}}\n| format     = {{hlist|[[Compact Disc single|CD single]]|[[Gramophone record|12\"]]}}\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Dance-pop]]\n| length     = {{duration|m=3|s=51}}\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros]]|[[Warner Music Group|WEA]]}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Sigurd Rosnes]]|[[Johan Aberg]]|[[Michelle Lewis]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|Sigurd Rosnes|Johan Aberg|Anders Hansson}}\n| prev_title = [[Alive Again (Cher song)|Alive Again]]\n| prev_year  = 2002\n| next_title = [[When the Money's Gone]]\n| next_year  = 2003\n}}\n\n\"'''A Different Kind of Love Song'''\" is a song by American recording artist [[Cher]], taken from her 24th studio album, ''[[Living Proof (Cher album)|Living Proof]]'' (2001). The song was written and produced by [[Sigurd Rosnes]] and [[Johan Aberg]], with additional writing done by [[Michelle Lewis]], and was co-produced by Anders Hansson. The [[dance-pop]] song alludes to themes of [[tragedy]], [[heroism]] and [[:wikt:brotherhood|brotherhood]], and was released as a double A-side single with \"[[The Music's No Good Without You]]\" in July 2002 through [[Warner Bros. Records]] and [[Warner Music Group|WEA]].\n\n\"A Different Kind of Love Song\" received mostly positive reviews from [[Music journalism|music critics]], who deemed it as one of the album's highlights, although noting Cher's heavily processed vocals due to the use of [[auto-tune]]. The song charted on a few ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' components, such as [[Hot Dance Club Songs|Dance/Club Play Songs]], where it reached number one, [[Hot Dance Singles Sales|Hot Dance Music/Maxi-Singles Sales]], peaking at number two, and on the [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary]] chart. No accompanying music video was commissioned for \"A Different Kind of Love Song\"; however, the track was performed a few times by Cher, including on a ''[[Will & Grace]]'' episode, her concert tour [[Living Proof: The Farewell Tour]], and during the [[American Bandstand|50th American Bandstand]] in 2002.\n\n==Composition and release==\n{{listen\n  | filename = Cher - A different kind of love song.ogg\n  | title       = \"A Different Kind of Love Song\"\n  | description = A 23-second sample of the song's chorus features Cher's heavily processed vocals over a [[dance-pop]] background.<ref name=ew/><ref name=am/>\n  | format      = [[Ogg]]\n  | pos = left\n}}\n\"A Different Kind of Love Song\" is a [[dance-pop]] song written and produced by [[Johan Aberg]], while additional writing was done by [[Michelle Lewis]], and [[Sigurd Rosnes]].<ref name=am/> Anders Hansson co-produced the song.<ref name=liner>{{cite AV media notes|others=Cher|title=Living Proof|year=2002|type=Liner notes|publisher=Warner Bros. Records|id=0927-42463-2}}</ref> According to Michael Paoletta of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', the track \"finds [Cher] not rocking the \"[[Believe (Cher song)|Believe]]\" boat too much: the chorus is soaring, the beats are foot-stomping, and the singer's vocals are gloriously affected.\"<ref name=bb>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-gsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA36|title=The Beat Box Hot Plate|last=Paoletta|first=Michael|date=July 13, 2002|accessdate=March 28, 2012|volume=114|issue=28|page=36|publisher=[[Nielsen Soundscan|Nielsen Business Media, Inc]]|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref> Jim Farber of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' perceived that Cher's vocals are heavily processed due to the use of [[auto-tune]].<ref name=ew>{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,216212,00.html|title=Music Review: Living Proof|last=Farber|first=Jim|date=March 11, 2002|accessdate=March 28, 2012|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Warner]]}}</ref> Lyrically, \"A Different Kind of Love Song\" alludes to themes of [[tragedy]], [[heroism]] and [[:wikt:brotherhood|brotherhood]], as noted by ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' journalist Barry Walters.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/living-proof-20020228|title=Living Proof - Review|last=Walters|first=Barry|date=February 28, 2002|accessdate=March 28, 2002|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=[[Jann Wenner]]}}</ref> The song was also treated with different remixes done by producers such as [[Rodney Jerkins]].<ref name=bb/> In an interview with [[MTV News]], Jerkins expressed that he was flattered to be working with Cher. He further added, \"It's incredible to be able to work with a true diva. Cher said she just wanted me to do my thing, which was the most incredible thing in the world. And I had fun doing it.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1455464/jerkins-talks-about-new-tlc-disc.jhtml|title=Jerkins Says New TLC Record Full Of 'Innovative Bangers'|last=Moss|first=Corey|date=June 28, 2002|accessdate=March 28, 2012|publisher=[[MTV News]]. [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]}}</ref> His remix was included on the 2003 compilation album ''[[The Very Best of Cher]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-very-best-of-cher-warner-bros-1-mw0000021651|title=The Very Best of Cher|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|date=April 1, 2003|accessdate=March 28, 2012|publisher=Allmusic. Rovi Corporation}}</ref> \"A Different Kind of Love Song\" was released as a single in July 2002,<ref name=bb/> with \"[[The Music's No Good Without You]]\" as its [[A-side]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Different-Kind-Love-Musics-Without/dp/B00006GA1H|title= A Different Kind of Love Song/ The Music's No Good Without You [Single] |accessdate=December 22, 2013|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nMichael Paoletta of ''Billboard'' considered the album version of the song \"perfect\", but questioned that \"it may be too upbeat for clubland\".<ref name=bb/> Reviewing ''Living Proof'', Jim Farber of ''Entertainer Weekly'' noted that the songs \"have enough oomph to make this more than a one-shot comeback,\"<ref name=ew/> while Kerry L. Smith of [[Allmusic]] selected it as a \"track pick\" from his album review.<ref name=am>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/living-proof-mw0000658398|title=Living Proof - Cher|date=February 26, 2002|accessdate=March 28, 2012|publisher=[[Allmusic]]. [[Rovi Corporation]]|last=Smith|first=Kerry L}}</ref> ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' called the song \"euphoric\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/cher-living-proof/35|title=Cher - Living Proof|publisher=[[Slant Magazine]]|date=January 21, 2002|accessdate=October 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\n\"A Different Kind of Love Song\" charted on few ''Billboard'' components. On the chart issue dated August 31, 2002, the song reached the top position on the [[Hot Dance Club Songs|Dance/Club Play Songs]], and peaked at number 30 on the [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=cher|chart=all}}|title=A Different Kind of Love Song - Cher|work=Billboard|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=March 28, 2012}}</ref> It also peaked at number two on the Hot Dance Music/Maxi Singles chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/living-proof-mw0000658398/awards|title=Living Proof Billboard Singles|publisher=Allmusic. Rovi Corporation|accessdate=March 28, 2002}}</ref>\n\n==Promotion==\nNo music video was made for \"A Different Kind of Love Song\". However, Cher performed it on the comedy series ''[[Will & Grace]]'' in 2002, where she made a special guest appearance in the episode, \"AI: Artificial Insemination Part 2\", as God.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=A.I.: Artificial Insemination<!--| url = http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0748739/-->|url=http://vimeo.com/8434630 |accessdate=March 28, 2012 |series= Will & Grace |serieslink= |network=[[NBC|National Broadcasting Company]] |airdate= May 16, 2002 |season=4|minutes=22 |time= |language=English}}</ref> The singer also performed the track during the first leg of the [[Living Proof: The Farewell Tour]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1459407/cher-extends-farewell-tour.jhtml|title=Cher Extends Farewell Tour|date=January 7, 2003|accessdate=March 28, 2012|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|publisher=MTV News. Viacom}}</ref> and on April 20, 2002, during the [[American Bandstand|50th American Bandstand]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/entertainment/slideshow/Cher-turns-65-15001.php#photo-1001667|title=Cher turns 65|work=[[San Antonio Express-News]]|publisher=Thomas A. Stephenson|date=April 20, 2002|accessdate=March 28, 2012}}</ref> A live video taken from [[Living Proof: The Farewell Tour]] is included as a bonus on the [[The Farewell Tour (video)|The Farewell Tour]] DVD.\n\n==Track listings==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n*'''CD maxi single'''<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=A Different Kind of Love Song|others=Cher|date=2002|type=US CD Maxi Single liner notes|publisher=Warner Bros Records|id=9 42455-2}}</ref>\n# \"A Different Kind of Love Song\" [Rosabel Attitude Vocal] \u2014 8:56\n# \"A Different Kind of Love Song\" [Murk Main Mix] \u2014 9:06\n# \"A Different Kind of Love Song\" [Ralphi's Alternative Vox] \u2014 9:47\n# \"A Different Kind of Love Song\" [Rodney Jerkins Main Mix - Faster] \u2014 4:19\n# \"A Different Kind of Love Song\" [Johnny Rocks Mixshow Edit] \u2014 5:58\n# \"A Different Kind of Love Song\" [Lenny B's Different Kind of Club Mix] \u2014 7:15\n# \"A Different Kind of Love Song\" [Craig J Classic Love Mix] \u2014 7:04\n# \"The Music's No Good Without You\" [Almighty 12\" Mix] \u2014 8:04\n# \"The Music's No Good Without You\" [Walter Tieb 