\"|7\n|-\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of number-one dance singles of 2002 (U.S.)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0000333|Cher}}\n* {{MetroLyrics song|cher|a-different-kind-of-love-song}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Cher (navbox)}}\n{{Cher songs part 1}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Different Kind Of Love Song, A}}\n[[Category:Billboard Dance Club Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Cher songs]]\n[[Category:2001 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Johan \u00c5berg]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Sigurd Rosnes]]\n[[Category:2002 singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = A Different Kind of Love Song\n| cover      = Adkols.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Cher]]\n| album      = [[Living Proof (Cher album)|Living Proof]]\n| A-side     = [[The Music's No Good Without You]]\n| released   = {{start date|2002|07}}\n| format     = {{hlist|[[Compact Disc single|CD single]]|[[Gramophone record|12\"]]}}\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Dance-pop]]\n| length     = {{duration|m=3|s=51}}\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros]]|[[Warner Music Group|WEA]]}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Sigurd Rosnes]]|[[Johan Aberg]]|[[Michelle Lewis]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|Sigurd Rosnes|Johan Aberg|Anders Hansson}}\n| prev_title = [[Alive Again (Cher song)|Alive Again]]\n| prev_year  = 2002\n| next_title = [[When the Money's Gone]]\n| next_year  = 2003\n}}\n\n\"'''A Different Kind of Love Song'''\" is a song by American recording artist [[Cher]], taken from her 24th studio album, ''[[Living Proof (Cher album)|Living Proof]]'' (2001). The song was written and produced by [[Sigurd Rosnes]] and [[Johan Aberg]], with additional writing done by [[Michelle Lewis]], and was co-produced by Anders Hansson. The [[dance-pop]] song alludes to themes of [[tragedy]], [[heroism]] and [[:wikt:brotherhood|brotherhood]], and was released as a double A-side single with \"[[The Music's No Good Without You]]\" in July 2002 through [[Warner Bros. Records]] and [[Warner Music Group|WEA]].\n\n\"A Different Kind of Love Song\" received mostly positive reviews from [[Music journalism|music critics]], who deemed it as one of the album's highlights, although noting Cher's heavily processed vocals due to the use of [[auto-tune]]. The song charted on a few ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' components, such as [[Hot Dance Club Songs|Dance/Club Play Songs]], where it reached number one, [[Hot Dance Singles Sales|Hot Dance Music/Maxi-Singles Sales]], peaking at number two, and on the [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary]] chart. No accompanying music video was commissioned for \"A Different Kind of Love Song\"; however, the track was performed a few times by Cher, including on a ''[[Will & Grace]]'' episode, her concert tour [[Living Proof: The Farewell Tour]], and during the [[American Bandstand|50th American Bandstand]] in 2002.\n\n==Composition and release==\n{{listen\n  | filename = Cher - A different kind of love song.ogg\n  | title       = \"A Different Kind of Love Song\"\n  | description = A 23-second sample of the song's chorus features Cher's heavily processed vocals over a [[dance-pop]] background.<ref name=ew/><ref name=am/>\n  | format      = [[Ogg]]\n  | pos = left\n}}\n\"A Different Kind of Love Song\" is a [[dance-pop]] song written and produced by [[Johan Aberg]], while additional writing was done by [[Michelle Lewis]], and [[Sigurd Rosnes]].<ref name=am/> Anders Hansson co-produced the song.<ref name=liner>{{cite AV media notes|others=Cher|title=Living Proof|year=2002|type=Liner notes|publisher=Warner Bros. Records|id=0927-42463-2}}</ref> According to Michael Paoletta of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', the track \"finds [Cher] not rocking the \"[[Believe (Cher song)|Believe]]\" boat too much: the chorus is soaring, the beats are foot-stomping, and the singer's vocals are gloriously affected.\"<ref name=bb>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-gsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA36|title=The Beat Box Hot Plate|last=Paoletta|first=Michael|date=July 13, 2002|accessdate=March 28, 2012|volume=114|issue=28|page=36|publisher=[[Nielsen Soundscan|Nielsen Business Media, Inc]]|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref> Jim Farber of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' perceived that Cher's vocals are heavily processed due to the use of [[auto-tune]].<ref name=ew>{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,216212,00.html|title=Music Review: Living Proof|last=Farber|first=Jim|date=March 11, 2002|accessdate=March 28, 2012|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Warner]]}}</ref> Lyrically, \"A Different Kind of Love Song\" alludes to themes of [[tragedy]], [[heroism]] and [[:wikt:brotherhood|brotherhood]], as noted by ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' journalist Barry Walters.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/living-proof-20020228|title=Living Proof - Review|last=Walters|first=Barry|date=February 28, 2002|accessdate=March 28, 2002|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=[[Jann Wenner]]}}</ref> The song was also treated with different remixes done by producers such as [[Rodney Jerkins]].<ref name=bb/> In an interview with [[MTV News]], Jerkins expressed that he was flattered to be working with Cher. He further added, \"It's incredible to be able to work with a true diva. Cher said she just wanted me to do my thing, which was the most incredible thing in the world. And I had fun doing it.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1455464/jerkins-talks-about-new-tlc-disc.jhtml|title=Jerkins Says New TLC Record Full Of 'Innovative Bangers'|last=Moss|first=Corey|date=June 28, 2002|accessdate=March 28, 2012|publisher=[[MTV News]]. [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]}}</ref> His remix was included on the 2003 compilation album ''[[The Very Best of Cher]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-very-best-of-cher-warner-bros-1-mw0000021651|title=The Very Best of Cher|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|date=April 1, 2003|accessdate=March 28, 2012|publisher=Allmusic. Rovi Corporation}}</ref> \"A Different Kind of Love Song\" was released as a single on July 2002,<ref name=bb/> with \"[[The Music's No Good Without You]]\" as its [[A-side]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Different-Kind-Love-Musics-Without/dp/B00006GA1H|title= A Different Kind of Love Song/ The Music's No Good Without You [Single] |accessdate=December 22, 2013|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nMichael Paoletta of ''Billboard'' considered the album version of the song \"perfect\", but questioned that \"it may be too upbeat for clubland\".<ref name=bb/> Reviewing ''Living Proof'', Jim Farber of ''Entertainer Weekly'' noted that the songs \"have enough oomph to make this more than a one-shot comeback,\"<ref name=ew/> while Kerry L. Smith of [[Allmusic]] selected it as a \"track pick\" from his album review.<ref name=am>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/living-proof-mw0000658398|title=Living Proof - Cher|date=February 26, 2002|accessdate=March 28, 2012|publisher=[[Allmusic]]. [[Rovi Corporation]]|last=Smith|first=Kerry L}}</ref> ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' called the song \"euphoric\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/cher-living-proof/35|title=Cher - Living Proof|publisher=[[Slant Magazine]]|date=January 21, 2002|accessdate=October 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\n\"A Different Kind of Love Song\" charted on few ''Billboard'' components. On the chart issue dated August 31, 2002, the song reached the top position on the [[Hot Dance Club Songs|Dance/Club Play Songs]], and peaked at number 30 on the [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=cher|chart=all}}|title=A Different Kind of Love Song - Cher|work=Billboard|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=March 28, 2012}}</ref> It also peaked at number two on the Hot Dance Music/Maxi Singles chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/living-proof-mw0000658398/awards|title=Living Proof Billboard Singles|publisher=Allmusic. Rovi Corporation|accessdate=March 28, 2002}}</ref>\n\n==Promotion==\nNo music video was made for \"A Different Kind of Love Song\". However, Cher performed it on the comedy series ''[[Will & Grace]]'' in 2002, where she made a special guest appearance in the episode, \"AI: Artificial Insemination Part 2\", as God.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=A.I.: Artificial Insemination<!--| url = http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0748739/-->|url=http://vimeo.com/8434630 |accessdate=March 28, 2012 |series= Will & Grace |serieslink= |network=[[NBC|National Broadcasting Company]] |airdate= May 16, 2002 |season=4|minutes=22 |time= |language=English}}</ref> The singer also performed the track during the first leg of the [[Living Proof: The Farewell Tour]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1459407/cher-extends-farewell-tour.jhtml|title=Cher Extends Farewell Tour|date=January 7, 2003|accessdate=March 28, 2012|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|publisher=MTV News. Viacom}}</ref> and on April 20, 2002, during the [[American Bandstand|50th American Bandstand]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/entertainment/slideshow/Cher-turns-65-15001.php#photo-1001667|title=Cher turns 65|work=[[San Antonio Express-News]]|publisher=Thomas A. Stephenson|date=April 20, 2002|accessdate=March 28, 2012}}</ref> A live video taken from [[Living Proof: The Farewell Tour]] is included as a bonus on the [[The Farewell Tour (video)|The Farewell Tour]] DVD.\n\n==Track listings==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n*'''CD maxi single'''<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=A Different Kind of Love Song|others=Cher|date=2002|type=US CD Maxi Single liner notes|publisher=Warner Bros Records|id=9 42455-2}}</ref>\n# \"A Different Kind of Love Song\" [Rosabel Attitude Vocal] \u2014 8:56\n# \"A Different Kind of Love Song\" [Murk Main Mix] \u2014 9:06\n# \"A Different Kind of Love Song\" [Ralphi's Alternative Vox] \u2014 9:47\n# \"A Different Kind of Love Song\" [Rodney Jerkins Main Mix - Faster] \u2014 4:19\n# \"A Different Kind of Love Song\" [Johnny Rocks Mixshow Edit] \u2014 5:58\n# \"A Different Kind of Love Song\" [Lenny B's Different Kind of Club Mix] \u2014 7:15\n# \"A Different Kind of Love Song\" [Craig J Classic Love Mix] \u2014 7:04\n# \"The Music's No Good Without You\" [Almighty 12\" Mix] \u2014 8:04\n# \"The Music's No Good Without You\" [Walter Tieb Mix] \u2014 7:40\n{{col-2}}\n*'''12\" vinyl'''<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=A Different Kind of Love Song|others=Cher|date=2002|type=US 12\" liner notes|publisher=Warner Bros Records|id=0-42455}}</ref>\n# \"A Different Kind of Love Song\" [Rosabel Attitude Vocal] \u2014 8:56\n# \"A Different Kind of Love Song\" [Craig J Classic Love Mix] \u2014 7:04\n# \"A Different Kind of Love Song\" [Murk Main Mix] \u2014 9:06\n# \"A Different Kind of Love Song\" [Rodney Jerkins Main Mix - Faster] \u2014 4:19\n# \"A Different Kind of Love Song\" [Ralphi's Alternative Vox] \u2014 9:47\n# \"A Different Kind of Love Song\" [Johnny Rocks Mix Show Edit] \u2014 5:58\n# \"The Music's No Good Without You\" [Almighty 12\" Mix] \u2014 8:04\n# \"The Music's No Good Without You\" [Walter Tieb Mix] \u2014 7:40\n\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Credits and personnel==\n*[[Cher]] - vocals\n*[[Johan Aberg]] - writer, producer, bass, guitars, keyboard, programming, mixing\n*[[Michelle Lewis]] - writer\n*[[Sigurd Rosnes]] - writer\n*Anders Hansson - producer\n*Neil Tucker - assistant engineer \n*Esbj\u00f6rn Gunnarsson - bass\n*Ziggy - backing vocals, keyboard, programming\n*Dennis B - keyboard, programming, mixing\n*Bj\u00f6rn Engelmann - mixing\n*Marie Diephuise - backing vocals\n\n:Credits adapted from ''Living Proof'' liner notes.<ref name=liner/>\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (2002)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardadultcontemporary|30|artist=Cher|accessdate=November 1, 2015}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboarddanceclubplay|1|artist=Cher|accessdate=November 1, 2015}}\n|-\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (2002)\n!Position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US Dance Club Songs (''Billboard'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/00s/2002/BB-2002-12-28.pdf|title=The Year in Music: 2002|work=Billboard|accessdate=November 1, 2015}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|7\n|-\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of number-one dance singles of 2002 (U.S.)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0000333|Cher}}\n* {{MetroLyrics song|cher|a-different-kind-of-love-song}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Cher (navbox)}}\n{{Cher songs part 1}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Different Kind Of Love Song, A}}\n[[Category:Billboard Dance Club Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Cher songs]]\n[[Category:2001 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Johan \u00c5berg]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Sigurd Rosnes]]\n[[Category:2002 singles]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eComposition and release:Typo fixing, replaced: on July 2002 \u2192 in July 2002", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Different_Kind_of_Love_Song"}
{"title_page": "Cathy O'Neil", "text_new": "{{short description|American mathematician}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Cathy O'Neil\n| image             = Cathy O'Neil at Google Cambridge.jpg\n| image_size        =\n| caption           = Cathy O'Neil at Google Cambridge in 2016\n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = \n| death_date        =\n| death_place       =\n| nationality       = American\n| fields            = [[Mathematics]]\n| workplaces        = [[MIT]]<br>[[Barnard College]]<br>[[D.E. Shaw]]<br>[[Columbia University]]\n| alma_mater        = [[UC Berkeley]]<br>[[Harvard University]]\n| doctoral_advisor  = [[Barry Charles Mazur]]\n| doctoral_students = \n| thesis_title = Jacobians of Curves of Genus One\n| known_for         = \n| awards            = [[Alice T. Schafer Prize in 1993]]<br>[[MAA's Euler Book Prize]]\n|website = [http://mathbabe.org mathbabe.org]\n}}\n'''Catherine''' (\"'''Cathy'''\") '''Helen O'Neil''' is an American mathematician and the author of the blog mathbabe.org and several books on data science, including ''[[Weapons of Math Destruction]]''<ref>{{Citation|title=The era of blind faith in big data must end {{!}} Cathy O'Neil|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_2u_eHHzRto|language=en|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref>  She was the former Director of the Lede Program in Data Practices at [[Columbia University Graduate School of Journalism]], Tow Center and was employed as [[Data science|Data Science]] Consultant<ref name=ColumbiaU>{{cite web|title=Talk by Cathy O'Neil at Columbia Institute for Data Sciences & Engineering|url=http://idse.columbia.edu/talk-cathy-oneil-mathbabe-924|accessdate=2014-02-26}}</ref> at Johnson Research Labs.\n\nShe lives in New York City and was active in the [[Occupy movement|Occupy]] movement.<ref name=\"pbsInterview\"/>\n\n== Education and Jobs ==\nO'Neil attended [[UC Berkeley]] as an undergraduate,<ref name=pbsInterview>{{cite web|title=PBS Interview|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/oral-history/financial-crisis/cathy-oneil/|accessdate=25 July 2013}}</ref> received a [[Ph.D.]] in [[mathematics]] from [[Harvard University]] in 1999,<ref>[https://www.genealogy.math.ndsu.nodak.edu/id.php?id=38230 Catherine Helen O'Neil], ''[[Mathematics Genealogy]]''.</ref> and afterward held positions in the mathematics departments of [[MIT]] and [[Barnard College]], doing research in [[arithmetic algebraic geometry]].<ref name=strataSched>{{cite web|title=Strata conference speakers bios|url=http://strataconf.com/jumpstart2011/public/schedule/speaker/125637|accessdate=25 July 2013}}</ref>  She left academia in 2007, and worked for four years in the finance industry, including two years at the hedge fund [[D. E. Shaw & Co.|D. E. Shaw]].<ref name=econ>{{cite web|title=Library of Economics and Liberty interview|url=http://www.econtalk.org/archives/2013/02/cathy_oneil_on.html|accessdate=25 July 2013}}</ref>  After becoming disenchanted with the world of finance, O'Neil became involved with the [[Occupy Wall Street]] movement,<ref name=\"pbsInterview\"/> participating in its Alternative Banking Group.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2011/12/ows-alternative-banking|publisher=[[Mother Jones magazine]]|title=Meet the Financial Wizards Working With Occupy Wall Street|author=Josh Harkinson|date=Dec 13, 2011}}</ref> In 2016, her book ''Weapons of Math Destruction'' was published and long-listed for the [[National Book Award for Nonfiction]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://nationalbook.org/nba2016_nf_oneil-weapons-of-math-destruction.html|publisher=[[National Book Foundation]]|title=2016 National Book Award Longlist, Nonfiction}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=http://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/the-national-book-awards-nonfiction-longlist|publisher=[[The New Yorker]]|title=The National Book Awards Longlist: Nonfiction|date=September 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe has founded [http://www.oneilrisk.com/ ORCAA] (O'Neil Risk Consulting & Algorithmic Auditing), which \"helps companies and organizations manage and audit their algorithmic risks.\"\n\n== Awards ==\nIn 1993 O'Neil was awarded the [[Alice T. Schafer Prize]] from the [[Association for Women in Mathematics]] and in 2019 she won the [[Mathematical Association of America|MAA]]'s [[Euler Book Prize]] for her book ''Weapons of Math Destruction''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gallian|first=Joseph A.|date=2019-06-01|title=The First Twenty-Five Winners of the AWM Alice T. Schafer Prize|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1090/noti1892|journal=Notices of the American Mathematical Society|volume=66|issue=06|pages=1|doi=10.1090/noti1892|issn=0002-9920}}</ref>.\n\n== Personal life ==\nO'Neil lives in New York City with her husband [[Aise Johan de Jong]] and their three sons.<ref name=mathbabeAbout>{{cite web|url=http://mathbabe.org/about/|accessdate=25 July 2013|title=mathbabe.org about page}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* With Rachel Schutt, ''Doing Data Science: Straight Talk from the Frontline'' (O'Reilly 2013, {{ISBN|1449358659}}).\n* ''On Being a Data Skeptic'' (O'Reilly Media 2013, {{ISBN|1491947233}}).  \n* ''[[Weapons of Math Destruction]]'' (Crown 2016, {{ISBN|0553418815}}).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:ONeil, Cathy}}\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:American bloggers]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia University faculty]]\n[[Category:Columbia University Graduate School of Journalism faculty]]\n[[Category:American women mathematicians]]\n[[Category:American women scientists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Science bloggers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American women bloggers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American mathematician}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Cathy O'Neil\n| image             = Cathy O'Neil at Google Cambridge.jpg\n| image_size        =\n| caption           = Cathy O'Neil at Google Cambridge in 2016\n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = \n| death_date        =\n| death_place       =\n| nationality       = American\n| fields            = [[Mathematics]]\n| workplaces        = [[MIT]]<br>[[Barnard College]]<br>[[D.E. Shaw]]<br>[[Columbia University]]\n| alma_mater        = [[UC Berkeley]]<br>[[Harvard University]]\n| doctoral_advisor  = [[Barry Charles Mazur]]\n| doctoral_students = \n| thesis_title = Jacobians of Curves of Genus One\n| known_for         = \n| awards            = [[Alice T. Schafer Prize in 1993]]<br>[[MAA's Euler Book Prize]]\n|website = [http://mathbabe.org mathbabe.org]\n}}\n'''Catherine''' (\"'''Cathy'''\") '''Helen O'Neil''' is an American mathematician and the author of the blog mathbabe.org and several books on data science, including ''[[Weapons of Math Destruction]]''<ref>{{Citation|title=The era of blind faith in big data must end {{!}} Cathy O'Neil|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_2u_eHHzRto|language=en|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref>  She was the former Director of the Lede Program in Data Practices at Columbia University Graduate School of Journalism, Tow Center and was employed as [[Data science|Data Science]] Consultant<ref name=ColumbiaU>{{cite web|title=Talk by Cathy O'Neil at Columbia Institute for Data Sciences & Engineering|url=http://idse.columbia.edu/talk-cathy-oneil-mathbabe-924|accessdate=2014-02-26}}</ref> at Johnson Research Labs.\n\nShe lives in New York City and was active in the [[Occupy movement|Occupy]] movement.<ref name=\"pbsInterview\"/>\n\n== Education and Jobs ==\nO'Neil attended [[UC Berkeley]] as an undergraduate,<ref name=pbsInterview>{{cite web|title=PBS Interview|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/oral-history/financial-crisis/cathy-oneil/|accessdate=25 July 2013}}</ref> received a [[Ph.D.]] in [[mathematics]] from [[Harvard University]] in 1999,<ref>[https://www.genealogy.math.ndsu.nodak.edu/id.php?id=38230 Catherine Helen O'Neil], ''[[Mathematics Genealogy]]''.</ref> and afterward held positions in the mathematics departments of [[MIT]] and [[Barnard College]], doing research in [[arithmetic algebraic geometry]].<ref name=strataSched>{{cite web|title=Strata conference speakers bios|url=http://strataconf.com/jumpstart2011/public/schedule/speaker/125637|accessdate=25 July 2013}}</ref>  She left academia in 2007, and worked for four years in the finance industry, including two years at the hedge fund [[D. E. Shaw & Co.|D. E. Shaw]].<ref name=econ>{{cite web|title=Library of Economics and Liberty interview|url=http://www.econtalk.org/archives/2013/02/cathy_oneil_on.html|accessdate=25 July 2013}}</ref>  After becoming disenchanted with the world of finance, O'Neil became involved with the [[Occupy Wall Street]] movement,<ref name=\"pbsInterview\"/> participating in its Alternative Banking Group.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2011/12/ows-alternative-banking|publisher=[[Mother Jones magazine]]|title=Meet the Financial Wizards Working With Occupy Wall Street|author=Josh Harkinson|date=Dec 13, 2011}}</ref> In 2016, her book ''Weapons of Math Destruction'' was published and long-listed for the [[National Book Award for Nonfiction]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://nationalbook.org/nba2016_nf_oneil-weapons-of-math-destruction.html|publisher=[[National Book Foundation]]|title=2016 National Book Award Longlist, Nonfiction}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=http://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/the-national-book-awards-nonfiction-longlist|publisher=[[The New Yorker]]|title=The National Book Awards Longlist: Nonfiction|date=September 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe has founded [http://www.oneilrisk.com/ ORCAA] (O'Neil Risk Consulting & Algorithmic Auditing), which \"helps companies and organizations manage and audit their algorithmic risks.\"\n\n== Awards ==\nIn 1993 O'Neil was awarded the [[Alice T. Schafer Prize]] from the [[Association for Women in Mathematics]] and in 2019 she won the [[Mathematical Association of America|MAA]]'s [[Euler Book Prize]] for her book ''Weapons of Math Destruction''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gallian|first=Joseph A.|date=2019-06-01|title=The First Twenty-Five Winners of the AWM Alice T. Schafer Prize|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1090/noti1892|journal=Notices of the American Mathematical Society|volume=66|issue=06|pages=1|doi=10.1090/noti1892|issn=0002-9920}}</ref>.\n\n== Personal life ==\nO'Neil lives in New York City with her husband [[Aise Johan de Jong]] and their three sons.<ref name=mathbabeAbout>{{cite web|url=http://mathbabe.org/about/|accessdate=25 July 2013|title=mathbabe.org about page}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* With Rachel Schutt, ''Doing Data Science: Straight Talk from the Frontline'' (O'Reilly 2013, {{ISBN|1449358659}}).\n* ''On Being a Data Skeptic'' (O'Reilly Media 2013, {{ISBN|1491947233}}).  \n* ''[[Weapons of Math Destruction]]'' (Crown 2016, {{ISBN|0553418815}}).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:ONeil, Cathy}}\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:American bloggers]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia University faculty]]\n[[Category:Columbia University Graduate School of Journalism faculty]]\n[[Category:American women mathematicians]]\n[[Category:American women scientists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Science bloggers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American women bloggers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "LumaNatic", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cathy_O%27Neil"}
{"title_page": "Gold dinar", "text_new": "{{disputed|date=January 2020}}\n{{refimprove|date=January 2020}}\n[[File:Dinar of Abd al-Malik, AH 75.jpg|thumb|Gold dinar of [[Umayyad Caliph]] [[Abd al-Malik ibn Marwan]] minted at [[Damascus]], [[Syria]] in [[Hijri year|AH]]&nbsp;79 (697\u2013698&nbsp;[[Common Era|CE]]) having a weight of 4.25 grams]]\n[[File:Dinar of Ar-Radi.jpg|200px|thumb|right|Gold Dinar of the 20th Abbasid [[Caliph]] [[Ar-Radi]] bi'llah (934 to 940 CE)]]\n[[File:Fatimid dinar - al-Moez li-dini Allah.jpg|thumb|Dinar issued during the reign of the [[Fatimid]] emir [[Al-Mu'izz li-Din Allah]] in [[Mansouria, Tunisia|Mansuriyah]] in 344 AH (955 AD)]]\n[[File:Dinar of Baybars.jpg|thumb|Dinar of the Mamluq sultan [[Baybars]] (658\u2013676 AH = 1260\u20131277 AD)]]\nThe '''gold dinar''' ({{lang-ar|\ufea9\ufef3\ufee8\ufe8e\ufead \u0630\u0647\u0628\u064a}}) is an Islamic medieval gold coin first issued in [[Islamic calendar|AH]]&nbsp;77 (696\u2013697&nbsp;CE) by [[Caliph]] [[Abd al-Malik ibn Marwan]]. The weight of the dinar is 1 [[mithqal]] (4.25 grams).\n\nThe word ''dinar'' comes from the Latin word [[denarius]], which was a silver coin. The name \"dinar\" is also used for [[Sasanian Empire|Sasanid]], [[Kushan Empire|Kushan]], and [[Kidarite]] gold coins, though it is not known what the contemporary name was.\n\nThe first dinars were issued by the [[Umayyad Caliphate]]. Under the dynasties that followed the use of the dinar spread from Islamic Spain to Central Asia.\n\n==Background==\n\nAlthough there was a dictum that the Byzantine [[solidus (coin)|solidus]] was not to be used outside of the [[Byzantine empire]]{{Citation needed|reason=The dictum needs to be referenced. Yet it seems irrelevant as the powers of Mesopotamia, Syria and Arabia, the heartlands of the Muslim revival, do pay tribute to the Roman Empire of Byzants, in spite of the anti-feudal sentiment of Islam prior to the Caliphate becoming an economic polity under Caliph al'Malik. The Islamic areas of the Caliphate are not yet perceived as being outside of the Empire.|date=December 2019}}, there was some trade that involved these coins which then did not get re-minted by the emperors minting operations, and quickly became worn. Towards the end of the 7th century CE, Arabic copies of solidi \u2013 dinars issued by the [[caliph]] [[Abd al-Malik ibn Marwan|Abd al-Malik]] (685\u2013705&nbsp;CE), who had access to supplies of gold from the [[Greater Upper Nile (region)|upper Nile]] \u2013 began to circulate in areas outside of the Byzantine empire. These corresponded in weight to only {{convert|20|carat|g}}, but matched with the weight of the worn solidi that were circulating in those areas at the time. The two coins circulated together in these areas for a time.<ref name=Porteous1969>Porteous 1969</ref>\n\n==First dated coins==\nThe first dated coins that can be assigned to the Muslims are copies of silver [[Dirhams]] of the [[Sassanian]] ruler [[Yazdegerd III]], struck during the [[Caliphate]] of [[Uthman ibn Affan|Uthman]]. These coins differ from the original ones in that an Arabic inscription is found in the obverse margins, normally reading \"in the Name of Allah\". The subsequent series was issued using types based on drachmas of [[Khosrau II]], whose coins probably represented a significant proportion of the currency in circulation. \n\nIn parallel with the later Khosrau-type Arab-Sassanian coins, first issued under the Well-Guided Caliphs of Islam, a more extensive series was struck with Khosrau's name replaced by that of the local Arab governor or, in two cases, that of the Caliph. Historical evidence makes it clear that most of these coins bear [[Hijra (Islam)|Hijra dates]]. The earliest Muslim copper coins are anonymous and undated but a series exists which may have been issued during the Caliphates of Uthman or [[Ali]]. These are crude copies of Byzantine 12-[[nummus]] pieces of [[Heraclius]] from [[Alexandria]].\n\n==First silver dirham==\n{{main|Dirham}}\n\n[[File:Silver Dirham.png|thumb|180px|Silver dirham of the [[Umayyad Caliphate]], minted at Balkh al-Baida in [[Hijri year|AH]] 111 (= 729/30 [[Common Era|CE]]).]]\n\nBy the year AH&nbsp;75 (695&nbsp;CE) [[Abd al-Malik ibn Marwan|Abd al-Malik]] had decided on changes to the coinage. A scattering of patterned pieces in silver exist from this date, based on Sassanian prototypes but with distinctive Arabic reverses. This experiment, which maintained the Sassanian weight standard of 3.5\u20134.0 grams was not proceeded with, and in AH&nbsp;79 (698&nbsp;CE) a completely new type of silver coin was struck at 14 mints to a new nominal weight of 2.97 grams. Unlike the contemporary gold coinage, this figure does not seem to have been achieved in practice. The average weight of sixty undamaged specimens of AH&nbsp;79\u201384 is only 2.71 grams, a figure very close to that for a unique coin of AH&nbsp;79 struck with no mint name (as was the standard procedure for the gold dinars produced in Damascus). These new coins which bore the name of 'dirham', established the style of the Arab-Sassanian predecessors at 25 to 28&nbsp;mm in diameter. Their design is composed of Arabic inscriptions surrounded by circles and annulets. \n\nOn each side there is a three- or four-line legend with a single circular inscription. Outside this are three line circles with, at first, five annulets surrounding them. The side normally taken as the obverse has as its central legend the Kalima or shahada: \"There is no god except Allah alone, there is no partner with Him.\" Around it is the mint and date formula reading \"In the Name of Allah: this Dirham was struck in [mint name e.g. Damascus] the year [e.g. AH&nbsp;79]\". The reverse has a four line central inscription taken from the Surah 112 of the Quran; \"Qul hu Allahu Ahad, Allahu-Samad, Lam yalid wa lam yulad wa lam yakul-lahu kufu-an ahad\"'. The marginal legend states: \"Muhammad is the Messenger of Allah, he was sent with guidance and the religion of truth to make it prevail over every other religion, averse though the idolaters may be\" (Quran 9:33)\n\n==First gold dinar==\n\nThe gold coins were first struck to the contemporary standard of 4.4 grams and with one or more Arabic Standing figures on the obverse and an Arabic legend on the reverse. Dated coins exist from AH&nbsp;74 and are named as 'Dinars'. These experimental issues were replaced in AH&nbsp;77, except in North Africa and Spain, by completely epigraphical designs very similar to the designs adopted for the silver pieces but with a shorter reverse legend and no annulets or inner circles. This type was used without appreciable change for the whole of [[Umayyad]] period, the coins being struck to a new and carefully controlled standard of 4.25 grams. This weight was reputed to be based on the average of the current [[Byzantine coinage|Byzantine solidi]], was called a [[Mithqal]], a term used earlier for {{frac|72}} of a ratl. Evidence of the importance attached to the close control of the new Dinars is provided by the existence of glass weights, mainly from Egypt. They usually show the governor's name, sometimes the date but all marked with coin denomination.<ref>Broome, Michael. \"A Handbook of Islamic Coins.\" (Page 11)</ref>\n\nThe issues in gold from North Africa began as copies of the coins of Heraclius and his son (but with an abbreviated Kalima in Latin), the reverse \"cross on steps\" losing in most cases its cross piece. Dinars, halves and thirds were struck, all to the new weight standard. Later coins are dated by [[indiction]], from Indiction II (AH&nbsp;84\u201385) changing to the [[Hijra (Islam)|Hijra]] date in Roman numerals in AH&nbsp;94 with Arabic phrases appearing in the field from AH&nbsp;97. In AH&nbsp;100, North Africa came into line with the eastern issues although the mint is named as [[Ifriqiya]]. The legends are shorter and the reverse has a new central inscription: \"In the Name of Allah, the Merciful, the Compassionate\". This was used also on the coins from [[Al-Andalus]], and on the half and third Dinars, most of which show no mint but may well have been struck in Al-Andalus.\n\n==Modern use==\n{{main|Modern gold dinar}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Money|Numismatics}}\n*[[Fals]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{cite book\n|last = Porteous\n|first = John\n|year = 1969\n|title = Coins in History: A Survey of Coinage from the Reform of Diocletian to the Latin Monetary Union.\n|chapter = The Imperial Foundations\n|pages = [https://archive.org/details/coinsinhistorysu00port/page/14 14\u201333]\n|publisher = Weidenfeld and Nicolson\n|isbn = 0-297-17854-7\n|url-access = registration\n|url = https://archive.org/details/coinsinhistorysu00port/page/14\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat}}\nAdam Abdullah, (2020, Apr.),The Islamic Monetary Standard: The Dinar and Dirham, International Journal of Islamic Economics and Finance Studies, [https://dergipark.org.tr/tr/download/article-file/1030977 6(1), pp.1-29]\n{{Dinar}}\n{{Islamic banking and finance}}\n[[Category:Gold coins|Dinar]]\n[[Category:Islamic banking]]\n[[Category:Economy of the Umayyad Caliphate]]\n[[Category:Medieval currencies]]\n[[Category:Islamic banking and finance terminology]]\n[[Category:7th-century establishments in the Umayyad Caliphate]]\n[[id:Dinar emas]]\n[[sq:Dinari islam]]\n[[vi:Dinar v\u00e0ng]]\n", "text_old": "{{disputed|date=January 2020}}\n{{refimprove|date=January 2020}}\n[[File:Dinar of Abd al-Malik, AH 75.jpg|thumb|Gold dinar of [[Umayyad Caliph]] [[Abd al-Malik ibn Marwan]] minted at [[Damascus]], [[Syria]] in [[Hijri year|AH]]&nbsp;79 (697\u2013698&nbsp;[[Common Era|CE]]) having a weight of 4.25 grams]]\n[[File:Dinar of Ar-Radi.jpg|200px|thumb|right|Gold Dinar of the 20th Abbasid [[Caliph]] [[Ar-Radi]] bi'llah (934 to 940 CE)]]\n[[File:Fatimid dinar - al-Moez li-dini Allah.jpg|thumb|Dinar issued during the reign of the [[Fatimid]] emir [[Al-Mu'izz li-Din Allah]] in [[Mansouria, Tunisia|Mansuriyah]] in 344 AH (955 AD)]]\n[[File:Dinar of Baybars.jpg|thumb|Dinar of the Mamluq sultan [[Baybars]] (658\u2013676 AH = 1260\u20131277 AD)]]\nThe '''gold dinar''' ({{lang-ar|\ufea9\ufef3\ufee8\ufe8e\ufead \u0630\u0647\u0628\u064a}}) is an Islamic medieval gold coin first issued in [[Islamic calendar|AH]]&nbsp;77 (696\u2013697&nbsp;CE) by [[Caliph]] [[Abd al-Malik ibn Marwan]]. The weight of the dinar is 1 [[mithqal]] (4.25 grams).\n\nThe word ''dinar'' comes from the Latin word [[denarius]], which was a silver coin. The name \"dinar\" is also used for [[Sasanian Empire|Sasanid]], [[Kushan Empire|Kushan]], and [[Kidarite]] gold coins, though it is not known what the contemporary name was.\n\nThe first dinars were issued by the [[Umayyad Caliphate]]. Under the dynasties that followed the use of the dinar spread from Islamic Spain to Central Asia.\n\n==Background==\n\nAlthough there was a dictum that the Byzantine [[solidus (coin)|solidus]] was not to be used outside of the [[Byzantine empire]]{{Citation needed|reason=The dictum needs to be referenced. Yet it seems irrelevant as the powers of Mesopotamia, Syria and Arabia, the heartlands of the Muslim revival, do pay tribute to the Roman Empire of Byzants, in spite of the anti-feudal sentiment of Islam prior to the Caliphate becoming an economic polity under Caliph al'Malik. The Islamic areas of the Caliphate are not yet perceived as being outside of the Empire.|date=December 2019}}, there was some trade that involved these coins which then did not get re-minted by the emperors minting operations, and quickly became worn. Towards the end of the 7th century CE, Arabic copies of solidi \u2013 dinars issued by the [[caliph]] [[Abd al-Malik ibn Marwan|Abd al-Malik]] (685\u2013705&nbsp;CE), who had access to supplies of gold from the [[Greater Upper Nile (region)|upper Nile]] \u2013 began to circulate in areas outside of the Byzantine empire. These corresponded in weight to only {{convert|20|carat|g}}, but matched with the weight of the worn solidi that were circulating in those areas at the time. The two coins circulated together in these areas for a time.<ref name=Porteous1969>Porteous 1969</ref>\n\n==First dated coins==\nThe first dated coins that can be assigned to the Muslims are copies of silver [[Dirhams]] of the [[Sassanian]] ruler [[Yazdegerd III]], struck during the [[Caliphate]] of [[Uthman ibn Affan|Uthman]]. These coins differ from the original ones in that an Arabic inscription is found in the obverse margins, normally reading \"in the Name of Allah\". The subsequent series was issued using types based on drachmas of [[Khosrau II]], whose coins probably represented a significant proportion of the currency in circulation. \n\nIn parallel with the later Khosrau-type Arab-Sassanian coins, first issued under the Well-Guided Caliphs of Islam, a more extensive series was struck with Khosrau's name replaced by that of the local Arab governor or, in two cases, that of the Caliph. Historical evidence makes it clear that most of these coins bear [[Hijra (Islam)|Hijra dates]]. The earliest Muslim copper coins are anonymous and undated but a series exists which may have been issued during the Caliphates of Uthman or [[Ali]]. These are crude copies of Byzantine 12-[[nummus]] pieces of [[Heraclius]] from [[Alexandria]].\n\n==First silver dirham==\n{{main|Dirham}}\n\n[[File:Silver Dirham.png|thumb|180px|Silver dirham of the [[Umayyad Caliphate]], minted at Balkh al-Baida in [[Hijri year|AH]] 111 (= 729/30 [[Common Era|CE]]).]]\n\nBy the year AH&nbsp;75 (695&nbsp;CE) [[Abd al-Malik ibn Marwan|Abd al-Malik]] had decided on changes to the coinage. A scattering of patterned pieces in silver exist from this date, based on Sassanian prototypes but with distinctive Arabic reverses. This experiment, which maintained the Sassanian weight standard of 3.5\u20134.0 grams was not proceeded with, and in AH&nbsp;79 (698&nbsp;CE) a completely new type of silver coin was struck at 14 mints to a new nominal weight of 2.97 grams. Unlike the contemporary gold coinage, this figure does not seem to have been achieved in practice. The average weight of sixty undamaged specimens of AH&nbsp;79\u201384 is only 2.71 grams, a figure very close to that for a unique coin of AH&nbsp;79 struck with no mint name (as was the standard procedure for the gold dinars produced in Damascus). These new coins which bore the name of 'dirham', established the style of the Arab-Sassanian predecessors at 25 to 28&nbsp;mm in diameter. Their design is composed of Arabic inscriptions surrounded by circles and annulets. \n\nOn each side there is a three- or four-line legend with a single circular inscription. Outside this are three line circles with, at first, five annulets surrounding them. The side normally taken as the obverse has as its central legend the Kalima or shahada: \"There is no god except Allah alone, there is no partner with Him.\" Around it is the mint and date formula reading \"In the Name of Allah: this Dirham was struck in [mint name e.g. Damascus] the year [e.g. AH&nbsp;79]\". The reverse has a four line central inscription taken from the Surah 112 of the Quran; \"Qul hu Allahu Ahad, Allahu-Samad, Lam yalid wa lam yulad wa lam yakul-lahu kufu-an ahad\"'. The marginal legend states: \"Muhammad is the Messenger of Allah, he was sent with guidance and the religion of truth to make it prevail over every other religion, averse though the idolaters may be\" (Quran 9:33)\n\n==First gold dinar==\n\nThe gold coins were first struck to the contemporary standard of 4.4 grams and with one or more Arabic Standing figures on the obverse and an Arabic legend on the reverse. Dated coins exist from AH&nbsp;74 and are named as 'Dinars'. These experimental issues were replaced in AH&nbsp;77, except in North Africa and Spain, by completely epigraphical designs very similar to the designs adopted for the silver pieces but with a shorter reverse legend and no annulets or inner circles. This type was used without appreciable change for the whole of [[Umayyad]] period, the coins being struck to a new and carefully controlled standard of 4.25 grams. This weight was reputed to be based on the average of the current [[Byzantine coinage|Byzantine solidi]], was called a [[Mithqal]], a term used earlier for {{frac|72}} of a ratl. Evidence of the importance attached to the close control of the new Dinars is provided by the existence of glass weights, mainly from Egypt. They usually show the governor's name, sometimes the date but all marked with coin denomination.<ref>Broome, Michael. \"A Handbook of Islamic Coins.\" (Page 11)</ref>\n\nThe issues in gold from North Africa began as copies of the coins of Heraclius and his son (but with an abbreviated Kalima in Latin), the reverse \"cross on steps\" losing in most cases its cross piece. Dinars, halves and thirds were struck, all to the new weight standard. Later coins are dated by [[indiction]], from Indiction II (AH&nbsp;84\u201385) changing to the [[Hijra (Islam)|Hijra]] date in Roman numerals in AH&nbsp;94 with Arabic phrases appearing in the field from AH&nbsp;97. In AH&nbsp;100, North Africa came into line with the eastern issues although the mint is named as [[Ifriqiya]]. The legends are shorter and the reverse has a new central inscription: \"In the Name of Allah, the Merciful, the Compassionate\". This was used also on the coins from [[Al-Andalus]], and on the half and third Dinars, most of which show no mint but may well have been struck in Al-Andalus.\n\n==Modern use==\n{{main|Modern gold dinar}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Money|Numismatics}}\n*[[Fals]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{cite book\n|last = Porteous\n|first = John\n|year = 1969\n|title = Coins in History: A Survey of Coinage from the Reform of Diocletian to the Latin Monetary Union.\n|chapter = The Imperial Foundations\n|pages = [https://archive.org/details/coinsinhistorysu00port/page/14 14\u201333]\n|publisher = Weidenfeld and Nicolson\n