tics]]\n[[Category:Christian mystics]]\n", "name_user": "173.73.87.106", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ellen_G._White"}
{"title_page": "Syed Fakhar Imam", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=May 2018}}\n{{unreliable sources|date=May 2018}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Fakhar Imam\n| office              = 11th [[Speaker of the National Assembly of Pakistan|Speaker of the National Assembly]]\n| successor           = [[Hamid Nasir Chattha]]\n| party               = [[Pakistan Tehreek e Insaf]]\n| deputy1             = \n| office1             = [[Ministry of National Food Security and Research|Minister of National Food Security]]\n| predecessor1        = [[Khusro Bakhtiar]]\n| successor1          = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1942|12|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = \n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| spouse              = [[Abida Hussain]]\n| children            = [[Syeda Sughra Imam]]\n| term_start          = 22 March 1985\n| term_end            = 26 May 1986\n| term_start1         = 6 April 2020\n| term_end1           = \n| predecessor         = [[Malik Meraj Khalid]]\n| deputy              = Wazir Ahmed Jogezai\n| office2             = [[Leader of the Opposition (Pakistan)|Leader of the Opposition]]\n| termstart2          = 24 March 1985\n| order               = \n| predecessor2        = \n| primeminister2      = \n| termend2            = 29 May 1988\n| primeminister1      = [[Imran Khan]]\n| successor2          = [[Ghulam Haider Wyne]]\n}}\n\n'''Syed Fakhar Imam''' ({{lang-ur|'''\u0633\u06cc\u062f \u0641\u062e\u0631 \u0627\u0645\u0627\u0645'''}}) (born 18 December 1942)<ref>http://www.pakistanherald.com/profile/syed-fakhar-imam-1169</ref> is working as the [[Chairman]] of [[Pakistan]]'s [[Parliamentary Special Committee on Kashmir]]<ref>https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2019/02/02/govt-to-appoint-fakhar-imam-as-kashmir-committee-chairman/</ref>. He also served as the 11th Speaker of [[National Assembly of Pakistan]] from 1985 to 1986.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.na.gov.pk/h_speaker.html |title=Speakers / Presidents |publisher=[[National Assembly of Pakistan]] |access-date=26 February 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100204000937/http://www.na.gov.pk/h_speaker.html |archive-date=4 February 2010 |df= }}</ref> On 6 April 2020, he was appointed federal [[Ministry of National Food Security and Research|Minister of National Food Security and Research]], replacing [[Khusro Bakhtiar]] in a cabinet reshuffle. He was educated at [[Clifton College]] in England.\n\nHis wife [[Syeda Abida Hussain]] was also minister in government of [[Nawaz Sharif]] and his daughter [[Syeda Sughra Imam]] is also a politician.He was preceded by [[Malik Meraj Khalid]] as Speaker of [[National Assembly of Pakistan]].He was elected to the national assembly and joined PTI.On 6 April he was appointed as Federal Minister for National Food Security\n\n<br />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Malik Meraj Khalid]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Speaker of the National Assembly of Pakistan|Speaker of the National Assembly]]|years=1985\u20131986}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Hamid Nasir Chattha]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Muhammad Saifullah]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Leader of the Opposition (Pakistan)|Leader of the Opposition]]|years=1985\u20131988}}\n{{s-aft|after={{nowrap|[[Ghulam Haider Wyne]]}}}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Leader of the Opposition (Pakistan)}}\n{{Speaker National Assembly Pakistan}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Imam, Fakhar}}\n[[Category:Leaders of the Opposition (Pakistan)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Aitchison College alumni]]\n[[Category:People educated at Clifton College]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the National Assembly of Pakistan]]\n[[Category:People from Khanewal District]]\n[[Category:Pakistani MNAs 1985\u20131988]]\n[[Category:Pakistani MNAs 1990\u20131993]]\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Pakistan Muslim League (N) MNAs]]\n[[Category:Pakistani MNAs 2018\u20132023]]\n[[Category:Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf MNAs]]\n[[Category:Federal ministers of Pakistan]]\n\n\n{{Pakistan-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=May 2018}}\n{{unreliable sources|date=May 2018}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Fakhar Imam\n| office = 11th [[Speaker of the National Assembly of Pakistan|Speaker of the National Assembly]]\n| successor = [[Hamid Nasir Chattha]]\n| party = [[Pakistan Tehreek e Insaf]]\n| deputy1 = \n| office1 = [[Leader of the Opposition (Pakistan)|Leader of the Opposition]]\n| predecessor1 = \n| successor1 = [[Ghulam Haider Wyne]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1942|12|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| spouse = [[Abida Hussain]]\n| children = [[Syeda Sughra Imam]]\n| term_start = 22 March 1985\n| term_end = 26 May 1986\n| term_start1 = 24 March 1985\n| term_end1 = 29 May 1988\n| predecessor = [[Malik Meraj Khalid]]\n| deputy = Wazir Ahmed Jogezai\n}}\n\n'''Syed Fakhar Imam''' ({{lang-ur|'''\u0633\u06cc\u062f \u0641\u062e\u0631 \u0627\u0645\u0627\u0645'''}}) (born 18 December 1942)<ref>http://www.pakistanherald.com/profile/syed-fakhar-imam-1169</ref> is working as the [[Chairman]] of [[Pakistan]]'s [[Parliamentary Special Committee on Kashmir]]<ref>https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2019/02/02/govt-to-appoint-fakhar-imam-as-kashmir-committee-chairman/</ref>. He also worked as the 11th Speaker of [[National Assembly of Pakistan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.na.gov.pk/h_speaker.html |title=Speakers / Presidents |publisher=[[National Assembly of Pakistan]] |access-date=26 February 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100204000937/http://www.na.gov.pk/h_speaker.html |archive-date=4 February 2010 |df= }}</ref> Since 06 April 2020 he has been appointed as federal minister for national food security .He was educated at [[Clifton College]] in England.\n\nHis wife [[Syeda Abida Hussain]] was also minister in government of [[Nawaz Sharif]] and his daughter [[Syeda Sughra Imam]] is also a politician.He was preceded by [[Malik Meraj Khalid]] as Speaker of [[National Assembly of Pakistan]].He was elected to the national assembly and joined PTI.On 6 April he was appointed as Federal Minister for National Food Security\n\n<br />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Malik Meraj Khalid]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Speaker of the National Assembly of Pakistan|Speaker of the National Assembly]]|years=1985\u20131986}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Hamid Nasir Chattha]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Muhammad Saifullah]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Leader of the Opposition (Pakistan)|Leader of the Opposition]]|years=1985\u20131988}}\n{{s-aft|after={{nowrap|[[Ghulam Haider Wyne]]}}}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Leader of the Opposition (Pakistan)}}\n{{Speaker National Assembly Pakistan}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Imam, Fakhar}}\n[[Category:Leaders of the Opposition (Pakistan)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Aitchison College alumni]]\n[[Category:People educated at Clifton College]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the National Assembly of Pakistan]]\n[[Category:People from Khanewal District]]\n[[Category:Pakistani MNAs 1985\u20131988]]\n[[Category:Pakistani MNAs 1990\u20131993]]\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Pakistan Muslim League (N) MNAs]]\n[[Category:Pakistani MNAs 2018\u20132023]]\n[[Category:Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf MNAs]]\n[[Category:Federal ministers of Pakistan]]\n\n\n{{Pakistan-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "PKahmed18", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Syed_Fakhar_Imam"}
{"title_page": "Wilfred Ussery", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=November 2017}}\n{{notability|Biographies|date=November 2017}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name= Wilfred Ussery\n|image=\n|alt=\n|caption= \n|birth_name=\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1928|10|11}}\n|birth_place=\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|office1 = 3rd National Director of the [[Congress of Racial Equality]]\n|term_start1 = 1968\n|term_end1 = 1969\n|predecessor1 = [[Floyd McKissick]]\n|successor1 = [[Roy Innis]]\n|alma_mater=\n|party=\n|spouse=\n|children=\n|website=\n}}\n'''Wilfred T. Ussery''' (born October 11, 1928)<ref>https://postnewsgroup.com/2018/10/19/wilfred-t-ussery-turns-90/</ref> is the former third National [[Chairman]] of the [[Congress of Racial Equality]] (CORE) in the [[United States]], having served from June 1968 to May 1969.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.core-online.org/History/wilfred_ussery.htm|title=Wilfred T. Ussery|work=core-online.org}}</ref>\n\nUssery also served as the Chairman of the [[San Francisco]] CORE. He was also the president of Black Urban Systems, a firm that consulted [[African Americans]] on getting control of services, institutions, and resources in their communities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.congressofracialequality.org/core-leadership.html|title=CORE Leadership|work=congressofracialequality.org}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ussery, Wilfred}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n\n\n{{US-bio-stub}}\n{{AfricanAmerican-stub}}\n{{Civil-rights-movement-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=November 2017}}\n{{notability|Biographies|date=November 2017}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name= Wilfred Ussery\n|image=\n|alt=\n|caption= \n|birth_name=\n|birth_date={{birth date|1928|10|11}}\n|birth_place=\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|office1 = 3rd National Director of the [[Congress of Racial Equality]]\n|term_start1 = 1968\n|term_end1 = 1969\n|predecessor1 = [[Floyd McKissick]]\n|successor1 = [[Roy Innis]]\n|alma_mater=\n|party=\n|spouse=\n|children=\n|website=\n}}\n'''Wilfred T. Ussery''' (born October 11, 1928)<ref>https://postnewsgroup.com/2018/10/19/wilfred-t-ussery-turns-90/</ref> is the former third National [[Chairman]] of the [[Congress of Racial Equality]] (CORE) in the [[United States]], having served from June 1968 to May 1969.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.core-online.org/History/wilfred_ussery.htm|title=Wilfred T. Ussery|work=core-online.org}}</ref>\n\nUssery also served as the Chairman of the [[San Francisco]] CORE. He was also the president of Black Urban Systems, a firm that consulted [[African Americans]] on getting control of services, institutions, and resources in their communities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.congressofracialequality.org/core-leadership.html|title=CORE Leadership|work=congressofracialequality.org}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ussery, Wilfred}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n\n\n{{US-bio-stub}}\n{{AfricanAmerican-stub}}\n{{Civil-rights-movement-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Baane247", "label": "safe", "comment": "included age", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wilfred_Ussery"}
